 the Planes and succeed.  In fact, pre-Kunark, that was your only option.  But if you don't want to have a CR that lasts for days (which was another hallmark of pre-Kunark planar raids), you've got to have a few basic requirements for these public raids.<br><br>The raid leader has to be able to limit attendance by class.  I know there are a lot of soloing druids out there who could really use those PoF drops, but even if the first 14 people who sign up are all druids, you can't take all of them.  So the raid leader has to be permitted to turn people away on this basis.<br><br>The raid leader has to be able to exclude people who are known ninja looters, generally disruptive, or otherwise beyond the fringe of acceptability.  This one is self-explanatory.<br><br>The raid leader has to be able to invite a small number of experienced people to flesh out the raid and make it work.  This might mean recruiting clerics for PoF.  It probably means bringing high level friends to pull and serve as main assist.<br><br>With today's equipment, either plane can easily be broken with a group or two of experienced higher-level players.  If you have these people in place, you can bring along a bunch of level 46-50 people and have fun farming armor drops and killing in the Planes all day.<br><br>Oh, and allow me to suggest as a hard and fast rule, no loot should be reserved on a public raid.<br><br>This, to me, is the ideal scenario for a successful public raid.  It's not as pure, and maybe not as public, as taking the first 36 people who sign up, but it's a lot more likely to work out for everyone involved.  If a raid leader doesn't have the discretion to do the things I mentioned above, the likelihood of a successful raid is slim.<br><br>Solonaro Stormheart<br>59th Outrider of Amici <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uwolfypaw.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wolfypaw